# Critical Performance Issue: RwLock in Hot Path

## Problem
The planmeca pool implementation takes a `parking_lot::RwLock::read()` on EVERY access to the pooled item via `Loaned::get()` and `Loaned::get_mut()`.

**Location**: planmeca/crates/pool/src/lib.rs lines 328 and 343

```rust
pub fn get(&self) -> &T {
    let slots = self.pool.slots.read();  // RwLock acquire on EVERY call!
    unsafe { &*slots[self.idx].get() }
}
```

## Impact
In the frame acquisition hot path, we access the pooled FrameData multiple times per frame:
1. `memcpy` into pool slot
2. Set frame metadata fields
3. Send to consumer

At 100 FPS, this means **300+ RwLock acquisitions per second** per thread.

## Solution Options

### Option A: Cache slot reference in Loaned (Recommended)
Store a raw pointer to the slot at Loaned creation time, eliminating per-access locking:

```rust
pub struct Loaned<T: Send + 'static> {
    pool: Arc<Pool<T>>,
    idx: usize,
    slot_ptr: *mut T,  // Cached at creation time
}

impl<T: Send + 'static> Loaned<T> {
    #[inline]
    pub fn get(&self) -> &T {
        // SAFETY: slot_ptr was set when we acquired the semaphore permit
        unsafe { &*self.slot_ptr }
    }
}
```

### Option B: Use UnsafeCell with index bounds check
Keep current structure but use atomic fence instead of RwLock:

```rust
pub fn get(&self) -> &T {
    std::sync::atomic::fence(Ordering::Acquire);
    // SAFETY: idx is valid for lifetime of Loaned
    unsafe { &*self.pool.slots_raw[self.idx].get() }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Loaned::get() and Loaned::get_mut() are O(1) without locks
- [ ] Benchmark shows <10ns per get() call
- [ ] Memory safety is preserved (semaphore still guards slot ownership)

