## New FrameProducer Trait Methods

```rust
// Add to FrameProducer trait

/// Register the primary frame consumer.
/// 
/// Only ONE primary consumer allowed - it owns frames and controls pool reclamation.
/// Call BEFORE start_stream(). Subsequent calls replace the previous consumer.
/// 
/// # Arguments
/// * `tx` - Channel sender that will receive LoanedFrame ownership
/// 
/// # Returns
/// * Ok(()) if registration succeeded
/// * Err if device doesn't support pooled frames
/// 
/// # Pool Reclamation
/// The pool slot is returned when the LoanedFrame is dropped by the consumer.
/// Slow consumers will cause pool exhaustion and frame loss/blocking.
async fn register_primary_output(
    &self, 
    tx: tokio::sync::mpsc::Sender<LoanedFrame>
) -> Result<()> {
    anyhow::bail!("Pooled frame output not supported by this device")
}

/// Register a tap for secondary frame access.
/// 
/// Taps receive copies (Bytes) or references, NOT ownership.
/// Multiple taps allowed. Can be registered before or during streaming.
/// 
/// # Arguments
/// * `tap` - The tap consumer configuration
/// 
/// # Returns
/// * Ok(handle) - Use handle to unregister tap later
/// * Err if device doesn't support taps
async fn register_tap(&self, tap: TapConsumer) -> Result<TapHandle> {
    anyhow::bail!("Frame taps not supported by this device")
}

/// Unregister a previously registered tap.
async fn unregister_tap(&self, handle: TapHandle) -> Result<()> {
    anyhow::bail!("Frame taps not supported by this device")
}

/// Deprecate subscribe_frames (keep for backwards compatibility during transition)
#[deprecated(
    since = "0.3.0",
    note = "Use register_primary_output() for zero-copy frames, or register_tap() for secondary access"
)]
async fn subscribe_frames(&self) 
    -> Option<broadcast::Receiver<Arc<Frame>>> {
    None
}
```

